\f0\b Subject areas to prioritize (at least one, preferably two):
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 \'96 Political economy of technology (AI, data, platforms, measurement)\u8232 \'96 Media, expertise, and knowledge production\u8232 \'96 Migration, borders, categorization, and state capacity\u8232 \'96 Cultural responses to economic or technological change\u8232 \'96 Institutions whose public narratives diverge from their actual functioning\

\f0\b Analytical constraints:
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 \'96 The article should interrogate a commonly accepted assumption rather than merely describe events.\u8232 \'96 Prefer pieces that link abstract concepts (incentives, norms, classification, legitimacy) to a concrete case or institution.\u8232 \'96 Tone should be skeptical or analytical, not celebratory, alarmist, or moralizing.\u8232 \'96 Avoid culture-war framing, hype about \'93the future of X,\'94 or managerial optimism.\

\f0\b Audience calibration:
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 \'96 Assume the reader is comfortable with theory and abstraction but impatient with jargon and introductory exposition.\u8232 \'96 Do not explain basic concepts unless doing so is itself part of the argument.\

\f0\b Style preferences:
